1 Introduction

There is a remarkable structural coincidence across mathematics and science: whenever a system is governed by the optimization of a functional in the presence of a small noise or scale parameter, the dominant behavior is Gaussian, and corrections are organized by the curvature of an underlying metric space. This pattern appears in:

    Bayesian statistics: Posterior distributions converge to Gaussians as sample size grows, corrected by the curvature of the Fisher information metric [1, 2].
    Statistical mechanics: Equilibrium distributions cluster around energy minima at low temperature, with thermal fluctuations governed by the Hessian of the Hamiltonian [3].
    Quantum field theory: The semiclassical (WKB) expansion expresses path integrals as Gaussian integrals around classical solutions, with loop corrections involving spacetime curvature [4].
    Machine learning: Stochastic gradient Langevin dynamics (SGLD) samples from Bayesian posteriors whose geometry is the Fisher‚ÄďRao metric [5, 6].
    Evolutionary biology: Wright‚ÄďFisher diffusion concentrates population distributions at fitness optima, with mutation supplying the small parameter analogous to temperature [7].
    Combinatorics: The saddle-point method evaluates generating function coefficients as Gaussian integrals around dominant singularities [8].

Previous work has treated each of these domains separately. We show that they are all instances of a single geometric principle:

    The Laplace‚ÄďSaddle-Point Principle. Every adaptive system minimizing an action S with small parameter őĶ behaves as a Gaussian process on the Fisher manifold (M,g), with all subleading corrections determined by the curvature of g.

Our main technical contribution (Theorem 3.1) is an explicit asymptotic expansion for Z(őĶ) on an arbitrary Riemannian manifold, with correction coefficients expressible as universal polynomials in the eigenvalues of H‚ąí1‚čÖRic(őł0‚Äč).

