7 Discussion
7.1 Summary of Results

This paper establishes four results:

    A universal asymptotic identity. The Laplace approximation on a Riemannian manifold, augmented by curvature corrections (eq. 5), is the unique asymptotic description of Gaussian concentration for arbitrary smooth action functionals.

    The Fisher metric as the universal correction geometry. The Ricci curvature of the natural metric quantifies the departure from Gaussian behavior in every application domain.

    Testable predictions. Two primary, quantitatively testable predictions (Predictions 5.1 and 5.2) and two secondary predictions (5.3 and 5.6) are experimentally accessible with existing data and standard computational tools.

    Effective parameter count. The geometric refinement of effective parameters (Theorem 5.5) provides a resolution to the interpolation threshold in double descent.

7.2 Structural Implications

A Noether theorem for statistics. Symmetries of S correspond to flat directions of g: where Ricij‚Äčvj=0 along symmetry orbits, the posterior is exactly Gaussian to first order in őĶ. Conserved quantities are precisely the directions in which the Laplace approximation is exact. Dually, directions of strong curvature are directions of maximum statistical learning‚ÄĒthe data is most informative about these parameters.

The emergence of classicality. The action S evaluated at its minimum is the "classical" solution; the curvature corrections ‚ąľőĶ quantify departures from classical behavior. Classicality emerges when the geometry of the state space is approximately flat near the classical path. In quantum field theory, this corresponds to the flat-field-space limit. In Bayesian inference, it corresponds to exponential-family models with large sample sizes.

A universal perturbation theory for adaptation. All domains in Table 1 share the same perturbative structure. A curvature compiler‚ÄĒsoftware that inputs (S,g,H,Ric) and outputs c1‚Äč,c2‚Äč,‚Ä¶‚ÄĒwould be a practical tool across disciplines. We outline such a compiler in Appendix C.
7.3 Limitations

    Multi-modal distributions. When S has multiple non-degenerate minima, the full Laplace sum (summing over all minima) is required. Our single-minimum result applies locally near each minimum; global effects (tunneling between modes) require instanton methods.

    Degenerate critical points. At phase transitions, detH=0 and the expansion breaks down. The singularity type of S at degenerate critical points is classified by Arnold's ADE hierarchy [15], and the appropriate generalization involves catastrophe theory. (See Paper 4 in this programme.)

    Non-compact manifolds. The integrals in (2) may diverge for non-compact M. Sufficient conditions for convergence (growth conditions on S, coercivity of the Hessian) are required. In practice, most statistical manifolds arising from exponential families are convex (hence bounded in the relevant directions), and the action grows sufficiently fast at infinity.

    Information geometry vs. spatial geometry. The Fisher metric measures statistical distinguishability, not physical distance. Curvature statements in the Fisher metric reflect the difficulty of statistical estimation, not spatial curvature in any physical sense. Conflating these is a category error that pervades popular accounts of "geometry of deep learning."

    Identifying őĶ across domains. The small parameter őĶ is structural (it identifies the scaling hierarchy), not physical. In Bayesian inference, őĶ=1/n where n is sample size; in QFT, őĶ=‚ĄŹ. The connection is formal.

    Computational cost. Computing the full Ricci tensor requires O(n3) operations (inverting H costs O(n3), and each component of Rij‚Äč requires additional contractions). For models with n>104 parameters, stochastic curvature estimators (e.g., Hutchinson-type approximations) are necessary. We outline one such estimator in Appendix C.

7.4 Outlook

The Laplace‚ÄďSaddle-Point Unity suggests that the Gaussian approximation is not merely a convenience but a structural inevitability: any sufficiently smooth optimization landscape, viewed through the lens of a small parameter, looks locally Gaussian, with curvature providing the universal correction language. This perspective has several extensions that we defer to future work:

    Non-equilibrium corrections for SGD with momentum (the geometric Langevin framework extends naturally to second-order dynamics).
    Information-geometric Ricci flow as a method for improving the conditioning of the Fisher metric during training.
    Categorical unification connecting the Laplace structure (Paper 2), Lyapunov exponents (Paper 3), and RMT universality classes (Paper 1) through a single categorical framework (Paper 9).

